f <-function(t){
  if (t==0){
    return ("very-low")
  } else if (t==1) {
    return ("low")
  } else if (t==2) {
    return ("moderate")
  } else if (t==3) {
    return ("high")
  } else {
    return ("very-high")
  }
}
#f(0)

Section D Explanations: 1). Correlation studies: Ho is True correlation is equal to 0 p-value = 0.999 (< 0.005) This indicates a strong positive linear relationship between the BMI and BP The box plot also showed that the association between the BMI and BP was positive That is: Increase in BMI leads to Increase in BP. Therefore, we reject the Ho.

Comparing difference in means Used the student t-test for unpaired samples Ho is True statistical difference in means = 0 p-value < 0.005 Interpretation: The the means are statistically different Therefore, we reject the null.

Ratio of variances F-Test was used to compare variances Ho is True ratio of the variance = one p-value = < 0.005 Reject the null since the ratio of variance was > one Also, the Ho value (one) is not in the CI for all.

2). Used the Chiq-test of two independent variables (Status and Gender) The expected frequencies > 5 Ho is there is No significant association between the two variables (disease status and gender) p-value > 0.005 We fail to reject the null Therefore, No statistically significant association between disease status and gender

3). Simple linear regression model was used (Assess effect of BMI on BP) BP - Dependent BMI - Independent p-value < 0.05 Thus, the entire model is statistically significant Also, the high R squired values imply a better fit (thus positive relation)

4). Two different variables: BMI is quantitative and Sampling locations being qualitative Used Oneway anova test Assumptions: Independent variables Parametric Equal population variances Ho: There is no significant difference in the mean BMI values in the 3 sampling locations p-value > 0.005 We fail to reject the null

5). Since we are dealing with Binary outcomes, we used the Binary Logistic regression model. p-value > 0.005 BMI and BP are not predictors of disease status.
